05942nam a22007215i 9780822384878DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223848787 a10.1515/97808223848782doi  a(DE-B1597)553355  a(OCoLC)1055305317  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 7aART0130002bisacsh04a745/.08222100aCrafting Gender :bWomen and Folk Art in Latin America and the Caribbean /ced. by Eli Bartra. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (255 p.) :b50 illustrations  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tAlways Something New: Changing Fashions in a ‘‘Traditional Culture’’ -- tThe Emergence of the Santeras: Renewed Strength for Traditional Puerto Rican Art -- tKuna Women’s Arts: Molas, Meaning, and Markets -- tConnections: Creative Expressions of Canelos Quichua Women -- tEngendering Clay: Las Ceramistas of Mata Ortiz -- tWomen’s Folk Art in La Chamba, Colombia -- tThe Mapuche Craftswomen -- tWomen’s Prayers: The Aesthetics and Meaning of Female Votive Paintings in Chalma -- tEarth Magic: The Legacy of Teodora Blanco -- tTastes, Colors, and Techniques in Embroidered Mayan Female Costumes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume initiates a gender-based framework for analyzing the folk art of Latin America and the Caribbean. Defined here broadly as the "art of the people" and as having a primarily decorative, rather than utilitarian, purpose, folk art is not solely the province of women, but folk art by women in Latin America has received little sustained attention. Crafting Gender begins to redress this gap in scholarship. From a feminist perspective, the contributors examine not only twentieth-century and contemporary art by women, but also its production, distribution, and consumption. Exploring the roles of women as artists and consumers in specific cultural contexts, they look at a range of artistic forms across Latin America, including Panamanian molas (blouses), Andean weavings, Mexican ceramics, and Mayan hipiles (dresses).Art historians, anthropologists, and sociologists from Latin America, the Caribbean, and the United States discuss artwork from Mexico, Argentina, Chile, Colombia, Ecuador, Panama, Suriname, and Puerto Rico, and many of their essays focus on indigenous artists. They highlight the complex webs of social relations from which folk art emerges. For instance, while several pieces describe the similar creative and technical processes of indigenous pottery-making communities of the Amazon and of mestiza potters in Mexico and Colombia, they also reveal the widely varying functions of the ceramics and meanings of the iconography. Integrating the social, historical, political, geographical, and economic factors that shape folk art in Latin America and the Caribbean, Crafting Gender sheds much-needed light on a rich body of art and the women who create it.ContributorsEli BartraRonald J. DuncanDolores JulianoBetty LaDukeLourdes Rejón PatrónSally PriceMaría de Jesús Rodríguez-ShadowMari Lyn SalvadorNorma ValleDorothea Scott Whitten  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aFolk artzCaribbean Area. 0aFolk artzLatin America. 0aWomen artistszCaribbean Area. 0aWomen artistszLatin America. 7aART / Folk & Outsider Art.2bisacsh1 aBartra, Eli, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBartra, Eli, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDuncan, Ronald J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJuliano, Dolores, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabular